		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Cincinnati Ohio</placeName></p>
			<p rend="align(right)"><date>14<hi rend="sup">th</hi> December <hi rend="sup">5609</hi>&#47;<hi rend="sub">1848</hi></date></p>
			<p>Revd Sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">I have read attentively and with much satisfaction<lb/> <persName>Dr. Wise&#39;s</persName> address and your preliminary and appended remarks upon<lb/> it&#44; inserted in the Occidents of this month. You have both spoken out<lb/> and truly represented the many existing circumstances that are any thing<lb/> but satisfactory to those who among us appreciate the religion we profess<lb/> and the great part our nation has been destined to fill in the Divine<lb/> economy. Unless our people are now what they were when reproached as<lb/> in Isaiah&#8221; Who is blind but my servant&#63; Or deaf&#44; as my messenger<lb/> that I sent&#63; Who is blind as he that is perfect&#44; and blind as the<lb/> Lord&#39;s servant&#63; seeing many things&#44; but thou observest not&#58; opening<lb/> the ears&#44; but he heareth not&#44;&#8221; such appeals as yours &#38; <persName>Dr. Wise&#39;s</persName><lb/> cannot fail to rouse them to a sense of what they owe to their God.&#8212;to<lb/> society and to themselves. Through <persName>Mr. Gutheime</persName> you will learn<lb/> those appeals have produced their effect here. several members of the<lb/> three congregations of this city met and adopted the resolutions he<lb/> forwards you&#44; a copy of which is to be sent likewise to the Trustees of<lb/> each of the Synagogues. It is expected that the Trustees will jointly<lb/> convene a general meeting of their members and though the result<lb/> cannot be certainly predicted we cherish the hope that the meeting<lb/> will express their concurrence in the views taken by you &#38; <persName>Dr Wise</persName></p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>and resolve on appointing agents to attend the meeting proposed by<lb/> you both&#58; probably the congregations here may resolve to address<lb/> a circular to the several synagogues in the Union suggestive of<lb/> each adopting a similar course&#58; Your meeting may then present<lb/> the imposing character of a representation of all or of such of the<lb/> congregations in these states as are disposed to consider the expediency<lb/> and utility of forming the Union in question. Should the Trustees<lb/> of the Synagogues here convene a general meeting and the result<lb/> prove such as we wish I will then forward you from time to time<lb/> some details upon the objects&#44; effects &#38;c of such a union&#44; in order<lb/> that being disseminated through the occident the great importance<lb/> of the measure and the numerous benefits that may be expected to<lb/> accrue from it to the whole community of Jews may be generally<lb/> perceived. I am reverend Sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(3)">Yours truly</p>
          <p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">A A. Lindo</persName></p>
			<p><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
